The Withered Depths

Deep within the Forest of Confusion, past the disorienting mists, lies a
region the old druids called the Withered Depths. Here the corruption that
birthed the confusion mists has its source. The trees grow impossibly tall
and twisted, bark blackened with fungal rot, the mist thick with the stench
of decay.

This blight is not natural. It is an orphaned experiment.

Before their catastrophic collapse, the Spirebound Conclave's Prism Thesis
faction conducted field trials in these remote forests. They implanted
resonance crystals in old-growth root systems, attempting to merge living
plant matter with runic preservation magic. The trials appeared to succeed.
Then the supply routes collapsed and the Conclave never returned to retrieve
the crystals.

Without calibration, the crystal matrices continued to pulse, drawing
magical energy into feedback loops that warped the surrounding ecology over
centuries. Root systems fused into labyrinthine underground networks. Fungal
colonies absorbed fragments of preservation enchantments, gaining crude
directed growth. Trees that should have died persisted in animate rot,
magically prevented from completing their natural cycle.

A druidic order attempted to contain the damage. Their confusion mists were
not intended to protect the forest from outsiders but to quarantine the
crystal resonance. For centuries the quarantine held. Then the druids died,
not dramatically but demographically, their tradition requiring decades of
apprenticeship that recruitment could no longer supply. The last generation
fell at their posts, still performing containment rituals, their bodies
preserved and bound by the same crystal resonance they had opposed.

At the corruption's heart sits the Blightmother: a living organism merged
with mineral structure through magical binding, grown to monstrous scale
without oversight. A custodial entity with no master, no purpose, and no
stop condition.

The institutional guilt chain runs clear: Midgaard's sealed warrants
supplied condemned laborers to the Conclave. The Conclave's experiments
created the blight. The blight now threatens the trade routes the city
depends on.
